/**
 * Performance test of algorithms to compute exact integer squares.
 * 
 * The following possible square detection algorithm is used:</br>
 * 1. Return false if n has an odd power of 2</br>
 * 2. Return false if n&fastMod is not in the set of square rests of fastMod</br>
 * 3. Compute rest=n%m for several m and check if the rest is in the square rests of each m. return false if not.</br></br>
 * 
 * If steps 1-3 are passed we have a possible square, and a basic sqrt() computation is required to find out
 * if it is really a square of an integer or a false positive.</br></br>
 * 
 * @author Tilman Neumann
 */
/*
 * Implementation notes:
 * 1. The data between ">>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>" and "<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<" has been generated with class SquareRestAnalyzer.</br>
 * 2. Principally we would need to generate only the mod-lists for each "fastMod"; the required square rests could be computed at initialization.
 *    However, in Java the code with inlined generated square rest constants is notably faster.
 * 3. To stretch Java's limit of 64k code for methods/constructors/initializers a bit, the square rests for each mod
 *    are wrapped into a proper method.
 */
